      Crypto is fun for tradersA  model that I often use for cryptocurrency=
 is that it is  rediscovering  traditional  finance: In its early days, cry=
pto was=C2=A0a brand-new financial system, unsullied by the old evils of ce=
ntral banking, leverage, regulation, etc.; eventually people realized that =
some of those things were good, and started reinventing them. One way to re=
invent finance is for idealistic crypto technologists to invent banking, le=
verage, regulation, etc., from first principles, with cursory or no knowled=
ge of how the traditional financial system addressed these issues or why it=
 rejected other solutions. You would expect this to lead to flawed but inte=
resting results, whole new ways of doing things that might blow up horribly=
 but that might instead point the way to a better future.Another way to rei=
nvent finance is for, like, Wall Street derivatives structurers or high-fre=
quency traders or securities regulators to say =E2=80=9Cwait, I know this s=
tuff, lemme go do crypto where it=E2=80=99s easy and no one else knows it.=
=E2=80=9D Here is  a very fun story from Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Justina Lee:=
=E2=80=9CAll the fun that used to be had 30 years ago in the commodity mark=
ets and is no longer fun -- that fun is now in crypto,=E2=80=9D says [forme=
r Wall Street energy trader Trey Griggs,] the U.S. chief executive officer =
at GSR Markets in Houston.Griggs is among crypto newcomers deploying system=
atic strategies that are tried-and-tested in conventional asset classes -- =
price arbitrage, futures trading, options writing -- in a booming new corne=
r of finance. As more mainstream investors get behind Bitcoin, boutique fir=
ms are joining the likes of Mike Novogratz in an ever-broadening crypto ral=
ly that keeps breaking records. =E2=80=A6Take Mark Treinkman. After a caree=
r mostly at proprietary stock-trading shops like Chimera Securities, digita=
l money is renewing his passion for quant trading.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99=
ve been going through some of my old strategies and things that wouldn=E2=
=80=99t have worked in equities in decades have an edge in crypto still,=E2=
=80=9D he says.I assume that a lot of these strategies involve very sophist=
icated intellectual property and instincts built up over decades in high fi=
nance, but others are just, like, you can simultaneously buy a coin at $80 =
and sell it for $100:For a few minutes during trading on Wednesday, for exa=
mple, the price of Ethereum Classic jumped well above $100 on the Coinbase =
exchange. The digital token was trading at less than $80 at other venues, o=
ffering an obvious opportunity for investors to make money simply by buying=
 in one place and selling in another.Or there is money lying around for any=
one to claim as long as they can confidently use the word =E2=80=9Ccontango=
=E2=80=9D:And the opportunities pop up everywhere. For instance, when longe=
r-dated futures in pretty much any asset class trade higher than the spot p=
rice -- known as contango -- the former almost always converges to the latt=
er as the contracts mature.That=E2=80=99s popularized the crypto basis trad=
e, where an investor goes long the spot rate and shorts the futures.When Bi=
tcoin last peaked in mid-April, the December contracts were nearly 4% highe=
r than August which were in turn about 2% higher than the spot reference ra=
te, as speculators unleashed bets on rising prices.=C2=A0Obviously one aspe=
ct of this story is that if you are a futures trader or electronic market m=
aker or derivatives structurer in traditional finance, you work very hard t=
o scratch out a few basis points in a competitive industry. If you move to =
the much shaggier crypto industry, there is less competition =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0in the relevant senses of well-capitalized players with good technology =
and access to leverage and pricing models =E2=80=94=C2=A0and you can potent=
ially make a lot more money a lot more easily. If you work on Wall Street, =
you probably like money, so moving to a place that gives you more money is =
pretty tempting.But another aspect of it is that if you work on Wall Street=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly as a derivatives structurer or high-frequency =
trading developer=C2=A0or securities lawyer =E2=80=94=C2=A0you actually=C2=
=A0like this stuff. You are there because you are fascinated by structure, =
because you enjoy puzzling out the technical details of these mechanisms an=
d trying to find new ways to push on them. In traditional finance this is a=
ll sort of saturated and competitive: Not only is it hard to get rich by co=
ming up with a new derivative=C2=A0structure or trading algorithm, but it=
=E2=80=99s hard to even get the intellectual satisfaction of doing that, be=
cause so much of what is possible has already been done, and innovation ten=
ds to be technical and incremental. Whereas in crypto it can feel like more=
 of a blank slate, or at least, like a different foundation where it takes =
ingenuity to=C2=A0re-erect the old structures.=C2=A0Neither of these arbitr=
ages will last forever, of course. Eventually crypto trading will be as com=
petitive as traditional finance, and innovation in crypto markets will be a=
s difficult. But for now, if you are in the business of inventing the struc=
tures of traditional finance,=C2=A0reinventing=C2=A0those structures in cry=
pto might look like more fun.Elsewhere, a Goldman Dogecoin trader=C2=A0call=
ed in rich:A managing director is said to have quit Goldman Sachs in London=
 after making millions at Dogecoin.Sources say that Aziz McMahon, a managin=
g director and head of emerging market sales at Goldman Sachs in London, ha=
s resigned, allegedly after making money on Dogecoin the cryptocurrency cha=
mpioned by Elon Musk whose value rose 72 times between the start of January=
 and late last week.KYC=C2=A0One thing to think about, if you run a company=
, is how much crime your company should do.=C2=A0The na=C3=AFve answer woul=
d be that the optimal level of crime, for any company, is zero: Doing crime=
s is bad, it is forbidden, you should not do forbidden things, it is a pret=
ty basic argument.I suppose an occasional theme around here is that this vi=
ew is not quite right, and that the optimal level of crime for many compani=
es is somewhat higher than zero. I have  suggested  recently, for instance,=
 that a venture capitalist should want the level of securities fraud among =
her portfolio companies to be a bit higher than zero: If some of your found=
ers aren=E2=80=99t lying to you, you aren=E2=80=99t backing enough bold out=
-of-consensus founders. If you run an investment bank and you want aggressi=
ve rainmakers to pursue hard-won business in distant parts of the world, so=
me of them might do some bribes, and if you cut the level of bribes to zero=
 it might lead to unacceptable losses of legitimate business. Or just more =
simply, if you have tens of thousands of employees, some of them will be st=
ealing office supplies or whatever, and the costs of monitoring might be hi=
gher than the costs of some crime. In your personal life you might have an =
=E2=80=9Cabsolutely no crime=E2=80=9D rule, but in a large enough company y=
our enforcement will necessarily=C2=A0be somewhat statistical, and absolute=
ly zero crime might be hard to achieve and not worth it.But never mind all =
of that. What if your company=E2=80=99s business is crime? What if you are =
a Mafia family, or a ransomware hacking group? Clearly the optimal level of=
 crime is not zero: If your business is crime, you have to do crime to get =
revenue. But the optimal level of crime is also not=C2=A0infinite:=C2=A0If =
you do too many crimes, or crimes that are too bad, you will get in too muc=
h trouble. Doing more and bigger crimes should increase=C2=A0your crime-bas=
ed revenue, but it also increases the resources that officials will expend =
on trying to shut you=C2=A0down, and thus your risks of being stopped and p=
unished. At some point the lines cross, and you should forego some criminal=
 revenue in order to keep your legal risk manageable.This is more or less t=
he same calculation that regular businesses often make=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Cwe don=E2=80=99t want this piece of business, even though it=E2=80=
=99s very lucrative, because it has too much legal risk=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0just with a different baseline. An ordinary business wants to commit =
very few felonies, perhaps zero; a crime business wants to commit many. But=
 they both have to make decisions at the margin, about whether to commit on=
e more felony.[1]So for instance if you run a ransomware business and shut =
down, like, a marketing agency or a dating app or a cryptocurrency exchange=
=C2=A0until it pays you a ransom in Bitcoin, that=E2=80=99s great, that=E2=
=80=99s good money. A crime, sure, but good money.=C2=A0But if you shut dow=
n the biggest oil pipeline in the U.S. for days, that=E2=80=99s dangerous, =
that=E2=80=99s a U.S. national security issue, that gets you too much=C2=A0=
attention and runs the risk of blowing up your whole business.  So:The Fede=
ral Bureau of Investigation attributed the massive Colonial Pipeline breach=
 to ransomware created by a relatively new gang called DarkSide on Monday a=
s new details emerged about the group accused of carrying out the attack. .=
..In its own statement, the DarkSide group hinted that an affiliate may hav=
e been behind the attack and that it never intended to cause such upheaval.=
 Like some other ransomware groups, DarkSide offers to sell its malware to =
others in what is known as =E2=80=9Cransomware-as-a-service,=E2=80=9D accor=
ding to the cybersecurity firm Cybereason.In a message posted on the dark w=
eb, where DarkSide maintains a site, the group suggested one of its custome=
rs was behind the attack and promised to do a better job vetting them going=
 forward.=E2=80=9CWe are apolitical. We do not participate in geopolitics,=
=E2=80=9D the message says. =E2=80=9COur goal is to make money and not crea=
ting problems for society. From today, we introduce moderation and check ea=
ch company that our partners want to encrypt to avoid social consequences i=
n the future.=E2=80=9DIf you want to use their ransomware software to do cr=
imes, apparently you have to submit a resume demonstrating that you are goo=
d at committing crimes. (=E2=80=9CHopeful affiliates are subject to DarkSid=
e=E2=80=99s rigorous vetting process, which examines the candidate=E2=80=99=
s =E2=80=98work history,=E2=80=99 areas of expertise, and past profits amon=
g other things.=E2=80=9D) But not too good! The goal is to bring a midsize =
company to its knees and extract a large ransom, not to bring society to it=
s knees and extract terrible vengeance.Imagine being the chief compliance o=
fficer at DarkSide. People constantly come to you with crimes, and you are =
commercial, you are like =E2=80=9Csure go ahead do that crime,=E2=80=9D but=
 occasionally you have to stop them and say =E2=80=9Cno the reputational ri=
sk of that crime is too great, we can=E2=80=99t do it,=E2=80=9D and the sal=
es reps grumble that you are getting in the way of business.  Just like at =
a bank!Or here is an amazing DarkSide compliance story:In November 2020, th=
ey issued another press release stating they were creating a "sustainable" =
data leak storage system hosted on servers in Iran.As Iran is on the US san=
ctions list, this caused ransomware negotiation firms, such as Coveware, to=
 put DarkSide on their restricted list and no longer negotiate ransom payme=
nt for this operation."DarkSide's own TOR site announces the intent to use =
infrastructure hosted within Iran, a sanctioned nexus. The purpose of this =
infrastructure is to store data stolen from victims of ransom attacks.""It =
is probable that a portion of the proceeds from any prospective ransom paym=
ent to DarkSide would be used to pay services providers within Iran. =C2=A0=
Accordingly, we have placed DarkSide on our restricted list," Coveware CEO =
Bill Siegel told BleepingComputer.DarkSide eventually had to walk back thei=
r claims of working with hosting service in Iran for fear of losing ransom =
payments.See, hacking into companies=E2=80=99 computers and making them use=
less=C2=A0until you get a Bitcoin ransom is a=C2=A0crime, but it=E2=80=99s =
a crime that has a legal infrastructure built up around it. You do the crim=
e, a legal ransomware negotiation firm sends you the money, it all runs on =
well-maintained tracks. But you move your servers to=C2=A0Iran, and you imp=
licate a whole different=C2=A0legal regime: Sure sure sure U.S. companies c=
an pay ransoms to=C2=A0Russian crime syndicates, no problem, but=C2=A0doing=
 business with Iran=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0even in the form of sending money t=
o Russian crime syndicates with servers in Iran =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a whole d=
ifferent kind of illegal. Nobody can do business with you =E2=80=94=C2=A0ev=
en criminal business =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it would violate U.S. sanctions on I=
ran. Doing ransomware is a matter of standard business crime; sending payme=
nts to Iran is a matter of U.S. national security. You don=E2=80=99t want t=
hat.Whistle-blowersHere is a slightly stylized description of how the U.S. =
Commodity Futures Trading Commission=E2=80=99s whistle-blower program works=
:=09The CFTC extracts fines from companies that do bad things.=09It puts a =
portion of those fines in a pot labeled =E2=80=9CWhistle-Blower Program.=E2=
=80=9D=09The pot is capped at $100 million: If the CFTC extracts more fines=
 than that, they just get paid to the U.S. Treasury.=09Years after extracti=
ng a fine, the CFTC will pay=C2=A0a percentage of the fine to the whistle-b=
lower who helped extract it. The fine comes from the pot and reduces the am=
ount in the pot.=09The pot is not replenished until there is a new fine.=09=
Oh also the people at the CFTC who work on the whistle-blower program draw =
their salaries from the pot.This mechanism can work indefinitely if:=09The =
rate and amount of fines is predictable and steady or rising over time, and=
=09No single whistle-blower collects close to the entire $100 million.Like,=
 if you collect $1 billion of fines in the first year, and then pay $100 mi=
llion of awards to the first-year whistle-blowers in the second year, that =
is fine as long as you are also collecting $1 billion (or $2 billion, etc.)=
 of fines in the second year. The pot gets replenished. On the other hand i=
f you collect $10 billion of fines in the first year, and those whistle-blo=
wers come to you with claims for $1 billion of awards in the second year, b=
ut there are no fines in the second year=C2=A0because you did all the finin=
g already, then you just pay out the $100 million cap and close up shop. Yo=
u have no money left for the rest of the awards.And because the whistle-blo=
wer program salaries are paid out of the pot, you literally close up shop: =
The whistle-blower program officials get furloughed, there=E2=80=99s no one=
 left to monitor the whistle-blower phone lines, no more whistles get blown=
, there are fewer investigations, there are no fines to collect in the thir=
d year, etc.You could imagine a whole range of better solutions. (Instead o=
f capping the pot at an arbitrary $100 million, why not just make the pot e=
qual to =E2=80=9Cthe amount of fines we collect, times the percentage we pl=
an to give to whistle-blowers=E2=80=9D?) But government accounting does not=
 always pursue the best solutions. Anyway here=E2=80=99s a funny Wall Stree=
t Journal article:The Commodity Futures Trading Commission=E2=80=99s whistl=
eblower program is in turmoil over a potential payout exceeding $100 millio=
n to a former Deutsche Bank AG executive=E2=80=94one so large it would depl=
ete the agency=E2=80=99s whistleblower funds and has led it to seek congres=
sional action.The executive had provided information that helped CFTC and J=
ustice Department investigations that led to roughly $2.5 billion in settle=
ments with Deutsche Bank in 2015, including $800 million with the CFTC. The=
y alleged that the bank manipulated the London interbank offered rate, or L=
ibor, a benchmark interest rate used to set short-term loans for global ban=
ks. =E2=80=A6Agency leaders have contended there is no mechanism to pay the=
 bank executive and other applicants and keep funding the whistleblower pro=
gram.The CFTC pays whistleblowers from money it collects in enforcement pen=
alties. But the agency=E2=80=99s whistleblower fund can be replenished only=
 when it falls below $100 million. Penalties collected otherwise typically =
go into the U.S. Treasury.It would be difficult to quickly replenish the fu=
nd through new settlements after a large whistleblower award because many o=
f the agency=E2=80=99s penalties are $5 million or less, according to a per=
son familiar with the matter.In the abstract, =E2=80=9Ccollect a $2.5 billi=
on fine and then pay 4% of that to the whistle-blower who brought it in=E2=
=80=9D would seem=C2=A0good=C2=A0for the agency=E2=80=99s budget: It keeps =
the other 96% (or gives it to the Treasury, fine); financially, that=E2=80=
=99s a trade you should be happy with. But the accounting for it =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and the long delay between collecting the fines (in 2015) and paying =
the whistle-blower (in 2021, maybe) =E2=80=94=C2=A0means that instead it is=
 somehow a crisis.Also:Agency staffers wrote a memo last summer stating tha=
t the whistleblower did deserve a substantial award, according to the peopl=
e familiar with the matter.The agency=E2=80=99s whistleblower office could =
end up furloughed if the fund is depleted. The Government Accountability Of=
fice in October said there is no other mechanism to fund the office.Some CF=
TC officials have argued that the agency could find legal solutions, but th=
e agency=E2=80=99s leadership says there is no other option but to furlough=
 the whistleblower office staff if the large award is paid, according to th=
e people familiar with the matter.I have to say that it is sort of impressi=
ve that an agency=E2=80=99s staff would recommend paying out 100% of its bu=
dget to a whistle-blower and then furloughing themselves. Like, it was deba=
table that this whistle-blower actually deserved a payout; the CFTC initial=
ly denied his claim. The staff could easily have said =E2=80=9Cnope, he doe=
sn=E2=80=99t deserve it, keep paying us instead.=E2=80=9D Instead, they rec=
ommended paying the whistle-blower, in effect, out of their own pockets.NFT=
sI  write a  lot around  here about non-fungible tokens, and particularly a=
bout the rather salient subset of NFTs that consist of (1) buying a work of=
 art, (2) lighting it on fire, (3) filming it as it burns, and (4) selling =
some vague claim to =E2=80=9Cownership=E2=80=9D of the now-nonexistent art =
as a token on the blockchain. When I write about this I usually try to make=
 it sound as dumb as possible, but=C2=A0I can=E2=80=99t compete with the pe=
ople who are actually doing it. Here is a New Yorker Talk of the Town piece=
 about =E2=80=9CBurnt Banksy,=E2=80=9D the art-world pseudonym of a=C2=A0gu=
y who originated this kind of NFT when he, uh, burned a Banksy painting. He=
re he is:=E2=80=9CArt is whatever you want it to be,=E2=80=9D the young man=
, who goes by the name Burnt Banksy, said, laughing. =E2=80=9CDo I think I=
=E2=80=99m an artist? Yes and no. I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s even r=
emotely fair to compare me to someone like Banksy. I=E2=80=99m just trying =
to make a message.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And:Everything went as planned, except tha=
t the art work wouldn=E2=80=99t catch fire. Fifty thousand people watched l=
ive on Twitter as Burnt Banksy struggled to burn a Banksy.=E2=80=9CIt was t=
he worst thing in the world,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt took, like, fift=
een minutes for it to burn. Some of the comments on the video were, like, =
=E2=80=98This kid=E2=80=99s never burnt down the establishment before!=E2=
=80=99 =E2=80=9D (Another comment: =E2=80=9CI hate my generation so much lo=
l.=E2=80=9D )It goes on like that, but I cannot. He bought the Banksy print=
 for $95,000 and sold the resulting NFT for $380,000. I don=E2=80=99t like =
it, but I cannot fault the trade here.Incidentally what I said at the top, =
about traditional Wall Street people getting into crypto because it=E2=80=
=99s easy and there=E2=80=99s a ton of money involved, goes like a hundredf=
old for=C2=A0artists. It is definitely true that, for decades, the traditio=
nal fine-art market supported a certain amount of low-effort conceptual jok=
ing about the relationship between art and money. Duchamp signed a urinal i=
n 1917. Rauschenberg=C2=A0erased a de Kooning drawing=C2=A0in 1953. That Ba=
nksy print that Burnt Banksy burned was called =E2=80=9CMorons,=E2=80=9D fr=
om 2006; it depicts=C2=A0an auctioneer selling a framed piece saying =E2=80=
=9CI can=E2=80=99t believe you morons actually buy this,=E2=80=9D plus a sw=
ear word. =E2=80=9CLol I have done a dumb thing and called it art, now to m=
ake fun of people for paying for it=E2=80=9D is at least a=C2=A0century-old=
=C2=A0move in the art world.And so it has been taught in art schools and be=
come part of the contemporary artistic tradition, to the point that =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0while I know more derivative structurers than artists =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0I assume that a lot of young artists got into that racket because they h=
ave a genuine love for interrogating and parodying the financial structures=
 that support the art market. And they want to do that interrogating, and a=
lso get rich, but the space for it has narrowed: That market is saturated, =
Duchamp already did the urinal, there are only so many new and extreme thin=
gs you can do to create artworks that make=C2=A0fun of people for buying th=
em.=C2=A0And then along came NFTs! As crypto reinvented traditional financi=
al markets, NFTs have reinvented the traditional=C2=A0art market.=C2=A0And =
as crypto has progressed through centuries of financial history in the last=
 decade, so NFTs have progressed through centuries of art-world history in =
like a year, and now a major category of NFT is the conceptual NFT that mak=
es fun of its owner for buying it. But whereas that move was=C2=A0harder an=
d harder to do in the regular art world =E2=80=94=C2=A0because it had been =
done so many times, because artists and critics and collectors were so fami=
liar with it, because artists themselves wanted to do something=C2=A0new=C2=
=A0and that move was so old =E2=80=94=C2=A0it has been reinvigorated in the=
 NFT market. Crypto millionaires had not yet experienced being made fun of =
for buying NFTs, so it is a novel and exciting experience for them and they=
 pay a lot for it; artists had not yet created conceptual nothings=C2=A0on =
the blockchain, so that is an exciting theoretical novelty for them. Also t=
he money is good.Finance and art are both centuries-old traditions. If you =
are a practitioner within them, you probably care about those traditions an=
d find them beautiful, but you also=C2=A0experience them as a burden, limit=
ing what you can do and restricting radical innovation. Starting over on th=
e blockchain lets you enjoy the traditions you love while also doing someth=
ing new.Things happenInside  Pictet, the Secretive Swiss Bank for the World=
=E2=80=99s Richest People.=C2=A0Robinhood=E2=80=99s Big Gamble.=C2=A0New Am=
azon bond rivals yield on US Treasuries in record-breaking sale. Biggest Cr=
ypto Exchange Binance Briefly  Stopped Withdrawals.=C2=A0Meet the academic =
who has fired up moonshot investing.=C2=A0Commodities boom sends bulk shipp=
ing costs to decade highs.=C2=A0Vice Media Targets Valuation of Nearly $3 B=
illion in Proposed SPAC Deal.=C2=A0 Oatly Sees Valuation Possibly Over $10 =
Billion as U.S. IPO Nears. Bennifer are back. Odd Lots  blog. Elon Musk and=
 Grimes party with Miley Cyrus at crypto-themed =E2=80=98SNL=E2=80=99 bash.=
 =E2=80=9CAn Italian television personality who claims the title Prince of =
Venice, which is also the name of his Los Angeles restaurant and former foo=
d truck.=E2=80=9DIf you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy e=
mail form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you =
can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Th=
anks![1] For a legal business it=E2=80=99s more like a decision about wheth=
er to commit 0.1 more felonies =E2=80=94=C2=A0like, =E2=80=9Cthis deal is l=
ucrative, but there=E2=80=99s a 10% chance it=E2=80=99s a felony.=E2=80=9D
